<http://data.open.ac.uk/ontology/news-classification/examples-4.1.1> rdf:type owl:Ontology ;
    skos:note """
    We assume a knowledge base, kb, which contains a vast range of entities of different types, including people, organizations, countries, etc.  For instance, we may have an entity, jf_kennedy, belonging to kb, of type Person. Letâ€™s also assume then that we have a news item, ni12345, which talks about this entity.  Hence, we want to say that jf_kennedy is one of the (possibly multiple) topics associated with ni12345.  In order to do this, we introduce a relation, topicOf (Topic NewsItem), and its inverse, hasTopic (NewsItem Topic) and we state: 

    s1: hasTopic (ni12345 T(jf_kennedy)) 
    """@en ;
    skos:note """
    The axioms must infer the following:
     :t1 owl:sameAs :t2 .
     :jfk owl:sameAs :jf_kennedy .
     :jf_kennedy owl:sameAs :john_fk . 
    """@en
    .

:jf_kennedy a foaf:Person .
:jfk a schema:Person .
:john_fk a foaf:Person .
    
:t1 a nco:Topic ;
    nco:isTopicRoleOf :jf_kennedy .

:jfk nco:hasTopicRole :t1 .
:john_fh nco:hasTopicRole :t2 .

:t2 nco:isTopicRoleOf :jfk .

:ni12345 a nco:NewsItem ;
    nco:hasTopic :t1 .
    
:s1 a nco:Statement ;
    owl:annotatedSource :ni12345 ;
    owl:annotatedTarget :t1 ;
    owl:annotatedProperty nco:hasTopic
    .